 ## 2026-07-17
 
+- [x] **task_022: `vibe audit --history` performance — fork-storm removal + single-pass message scan** — `vibe audit --history` timed out at 280s on the vibe repo (~230 commits). Two causes, both in the task_019 content guard, both fixed with the finding set held byte-identical (the scanner is a security boundary shared by pre-commit/commit-msg/pre-push and `vibe audit` — a silently-narrowed rule is a shipped hole). (1) **Match primitives (Part A):** the five hot-path functions (`check_rule`, `check_email_rule`, `check_home_path_rule`, `is_named_trailer`, `is_trailer_line`) forked a `printf | grep -oE` (plus a `sed`) per rule per line — ~400k+ subprocesses over `git log -p --all` in pass 1 alone. Swapped to bash-native `[[ =~ ]]` + `BASH_REMATCH`; those bodies now contain zero external-command invocations or command substitutions (a permanent static-shape test guards against the fork-storm returning). Portability held to POSIX ERE for BSD `regcomp` (macOS bash 3.2) and glibc (container bash 5) alike — no bash-4 features, and the `mdns-local` rule's GNU `\b` word-boundary was rewritten to a capture-group POSIX form (`([A-Za-z0-9-]+\.local)([^A-Za-z0-9_]|$)`, snippet taken from group 1 so `foo.localhost` still doesn't match and reported snippets are unchanged). `set -euo pipefail` survival: every match test is guarded in an `if`/`&&`; `nocasematch` is set and restored on every path out of the icase branch (a leak would silently make later case-sensitive rules case-insensitive — an adversarial corpus line with a mixed-case secret trigger and an uppercase `FOO.LOCAL` proves it doesn't). (2) **Single-pass message scan (Part B):** new scanner mode `--messages-stdin` reads NUL-delimited `<sha>\n<body>` records (from `git log --all -z --format='%H%n%B'`), scanning each message line as `commit <sha>` — the NUL delimiter, not line-shape sniffing, is the record boundary, so a body line like `commit deadbeef` or `+foo` is scanned as content and never misparsed; empty/malformed records are skipped without crashing. `_audit_history` pass 2 collapsed from a fork-per-commit `--message`+awk loop (and its dead `tmp_msgfile`) to one pipe into `--messages-stdin`; passes 1 (`--blob-stdin`) and 3 (`--identity`) unchanged. Result: full `vibe audit --history` ~20.7s (was >280s), scanner ~24x faster on a 12k-line real-history slice; old-vs-new byte-identical across `--blob-stdin`/`--staged`/`--message`/`--range`/`--messages-stdin` on an every-rule adversarial corpus and on the real repo history. `--message` (commit-msg hook) retained unchanged; override/opt-out paths unchanged. shellcheck clean; full smoke suite green; scanner header comment + usage text updated.
+
 - [x] **task_021: commit-identity guard — scanner `--identity` mode + pre-commit gate + audit identities pass** — root cause of the 2026-07-17 cross-org email exposure was `setup-git.sh` silently inheriting the host's real `user.email` while nothing checked identity (≈2,300 public commits carried real addresses; the content guard and `vibe audit` only saw blob/message content, never metadata). Now: `vibe-content-scan.sh --identity [email]` WARNs (`commit-identity`) on any non-noreply-class commit email (exempt: `*@users.noreply.github.com`, `noreply@github.com`, `noreply@anthropic.com`, `placeholder@vibe.local`; `.vibe-content-allow` whole-line entries suppress deliberate identities); `pre-commit` runs it alongside `--staged` (both run, either fails the commit, fix/keep instructions printed); `vibe audit --history` gains a pass 3 that feeds every unique author+committer email from all refs through the same check as WARN findings. TDD: smoke tests task_021 AC1–AC3 written first and watched fail; AC10 fixture email moved to a noreply form (now correctly gated). Docs: content-guard.md fragment gains the commit-identity tier.
 
